<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1898-03-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1898-03-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="138" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Sherman</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Denby</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1898-03-21"><hi rend="italic">March 21,
                                1898</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 1553.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have to acknowledge the receipt of your
                            dispatch No. 2861, of the 4th ultimo, inclosing a copy of a decree of
                            the Emperor of China relating to the antiforeign riots in Shantung.</p>
                        <p>The provision in the decree, that “in the event of worthless and reckless
                            fellows again making trouble and committing acts of violence, the local
                            authorities of the place will be held solely responsible,” has been read
                            with satisfaction, as it affords a long-demanded guaranty for the
                            future.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully, yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">John Sherman.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>